defaultacademies.
default1.7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTKAT has four data collections a year: September, December, March/April,
default and July. All our academies report  on “looked after children” children on the SEN register,  English as an additional language and free school meals.  The data is collected by the academies and is available online to Regional Directors and the Educational Executive.  The data is interrogated rigorously and quality assured by TKAT.
default1.8.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe governors have the responsibility of holding the academy to account for narrowing the gap. The governors have training to enable them to interpret the data and challenge where necessary.  If the governors do not have the expertise then we 
defaultimmediately 
defaulteither put in a Regional Board to support governance or the TKAT Board approves additional skilled governors be appointed to governing bodies have training 
default1.9.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe data from academies is also available to the Regional Directors and other 
defaulteducationalists at TKAT central, who use this information to challenge both senior leaders and governors.
default1.10.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is only when the right model of governance is in place that academies can truly be held to account.
