default-
default warning notice.
default3.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIf an academy chain has “taken over” a failing school in a September then due diligence will normally have shown that the senior leadership and governance are failing.  The first task is to remove and replace the headteacher and  governing body.  Many of the staff will not know what “good/outstanding” looks like so a comprehensive and intensive model of professional development needs to be put in place.  Some staff will rise to the challenge of being held accountable for their classroom practice whilst others will decide to leave.  This exercise has to be followed up with a recruitment process.  It is quite possible for a school to join an academy chain, with poor results but a “satisfactory” or even “good” Ofsted report from 2 or 3 years ago.  The school could well dip further before it improves so sponsors should be given a minimum of two years to show accelerated progress.
default3.4.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAs the programme expands the DfE/Ofsted will have to understand more about how academy chains work and the quality assurance and school improvement programmes they have in place.  TKAT is currently working with Ofsted on joint inspections of a number of our academies to see what we can learn from each other.   At the moment neither the DfE nor Ofsted understand the effectiveness of our QA and school improvement model.
default  
